SENATE RESOLUTION 289
By Akbari
A RESOLUTION to commend Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc., on
the occasion of its 2026 Tennessee Days at the
Capitol and its Centennial celebration of social
action in the Southern Region.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should honor and specially commend those distinguished
organizations whose stated goals advance the most noble precepts of human endeavors and
whose history of service in pursuit of those goals stands as a shining example to the citizens of
this great State; and
WHEREAS, one such estimable organization that evinces the greatest integrity and
probity is Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc., an international organization composed of over
1,050 chartered chapters worldwide, representing more than 350,000 initiated members who
remain committed to Sisterhood, Scholarship, Service, and Social Action; and
WHEREAS, Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc., was founded on January 13, 1913, by
twenty-two collegiate women at Howard University to promote academic excellence and provide
assistance to those in need. The Founders' first act of public service was participating in the
Women's Suffrage March of 1913; and
WHEREAS, a wide range of programs and service to the community have been
implemented for over 113 years. The major programs of the Sorority are based upon the Five-
Point Programmatic Thrust: economic development, educational development, international
awareness and involvement, physical and mental health, and political awareness and
involvement; and
WHEREAS, Cheryl W. Turner proudly serves as the International President and Chair of
the Board of Directors; and
SR0289
012532
- 1 -

WHEREAS, the Southern Region was formed in 1926 and is the largest of the Sorority's
seven regions, spanning Alabama, the Bahamas, Florida, Georgia, Mississippi, and the Great
State of Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, Amaris L. Johnson is the twenty-seventh Regional Director, and Noel
Seymours is the Regional Representative; and
WHEREAS, on February 9-10, 2026, members from Tennessee's twenty-seven alumnae
and collegiate chapters, along with Southern Regional Director Amaris L. Johnson and Southern
Regional Social Action Coordinator Waikinya J.S. Clanton, will travel to the Tennessee State
Capitol to attend work sessions focusing on the sorority's social action priorities, build
relationships with legislators, and further engage in the legislative process; and
WHEREAS, Tennessee boasts impressive leadership with Keena Alexander as State
Coordinator, Elise Russ as State Facilitator, Tamara Bates-Cast and Celia Q. Conley as State
Social Action Coordinators and Delta Days at the Capitol Chairs, and Christiane Buggs-Frazier,
Herbernita Jenkins, Kenya McGruder, Vivian Wilhoite, and Chandra Vasser as Nashville
Chapter hostesses; and
WHEREAS, it is the policy of the Senate to celebrate exceptional organizations,
especially those such as Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc., whose extraordinary community
service and advocacy bring honor to the State of Tennessee and improve the lives of future
generations of Tennesseans; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we commend the members of
Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc., for upon the occasion of their Tennessee Days at the Capitol,
extending our gratitude for their exemplary service to their respective communities and
applauding their efforts to improve the policies of the State and the well-being of its citizens.
- 2 - 012532

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
